Xev</center></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2F2F4F><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/ufrodlin7th.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Frodlin7th</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>is a Formidable Opponent</span><br>  Posts: 131<br> <font color=#FF0000>(9/28/02 1:01:31 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub14.ezboard.com/fthesteelwarriorthearena.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2145.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Raiding Strategies</span><hr size=1> Warrior Raiding Responsibilites:<br>
<br>
Pre-Raid:<br>
<br>
1. Know where, what time, what zone you're meeting in, learn something about the zone, and what is expected to be encountered.<br>
<br>
2. Know who the raid leader is, and what role is expected of you.<br>
<br>
3. Arrange IN ADVANCE, transportation to the zone where you'll be meeting up in.<br>
<br>
4. Make certain that you're bound in a location which is close enough to a druid and wizard portal so that if you need a ride back at any time, it's convenient for them.<br>
<br>
5. Get supplies (food/drink/arrows) in advance.<br>
<br>
6. If there's a reagent cost (Hate or Airstones) and you've been asked to compensate for this, make sure you bring it and direct it to the right source.  If you're unsure of this, ask your raid leader.<br>
<br>
Raid Type 1:  Generic Zone Raid:<br>
<br>
Examples:<br>
<br>
Plane of Hate, Plane of Fear, Chardok.<br>
<br>
You will generally buff before heading up, and invis if necessary.  While your group leader may be responsible for ensureing that their party is properly buffed, ultimately it is the individual's responsibility to ensure that they are buffed with the most reasonable buff set for your class.  <br>
<br>
For a warrior this is generally a &quot;raid type&quot; buffset.<br>
<br>
Armor Class Buffs (Generally cleric buffs)<br>
Hitpoint Buffs (Generally Symbols/Talismans, or any o the &quot;all purpose buffs&quot; like Harnessing of Spirit, Focus of Spirit, or Aegolism)<br>
Stamina Buffs<br>
Any necessary resist buffs<br>
And Haste<br>
<br>
In a &quot;zone raid&quot;, the goal is to kill monsters as efficiently as possible.  Generally (barring Kael for instance), most monsters can be mesmerized by an enchanter.   Because of this, two things are of dire importance.  First, to find out who the &quot;Main Assist&quot; is, second, to set up a hotkey which says &quot;/assist (Main Assist)&quot;.  What is going to happen is that in the event that multiple monsters come, everyone should attack the same target to keep the others under control and to quickly dispose of one and move on to the next.  The &quot;Main Assist&quot; is the person who's job it is to select those targets, an notify the raid that he's attacking.  Once you see him or her say &quot;Assist Me with (target)&quot; you will hit your /assist key and then attack.   It is generally considered important to wait until the Main Assist has made the call, no matter what before attacking, or you could be breaking mesmerizations and the monsters will have Enchanter for lunch.  <br>
<br>
On many raids a Secondary Assist will be called out in advance in he lik...err.. unlikely event the Main Assist dies.  What the Secondary Assist also does is what is called &quot;Tank-Mezzing&quot;.  In some instances, there are monsters that are immune to Mesmerization spells.   This requires someone to be actively beat upon in order to kep them busy while the rest of the raid is killing the primary target.  Each raid member should have an assist key made for at least the MA (Main Assist), the SA (Secondary Assist), and TA (Third assist).  This keeps things well organized and under control.<br>
<br>
Other things to be aware of... if you are going to go Away from keyboard, your responsibility is to let the raid know this and to target someone in your group to autofollow.   This way you don't get left behind if the raid moves while you're away.<br>
<br>
If you have been selected to be the Main Assist... you have your work cut out for you.  Before things start, have a discussion with the enchanter there, and determine in advance which monsters are harder or impossible to mesmerize.   This will aid you greatly in selecting the most appropriate monster to target and tell the raid to kill first.  Hard to Mez, or Impossible to mez monsters represent the greatest threat to your enchanters, and because of this, it's of crucial importance that you kill them without causing undue aggro to be put on your enchanters.  Once the greater threats are disposed of, you can move on to the lesser threats.<br>
<br>
Before you attack a mesmerized target, taunt it a couple of times...it may actually work, and keep the enchanter from being beaten upon.   Make a hotkey of your own where there is NO mistaking what your target is or whether it's you calling assist.  I'd recommend using Capitol Letters and try to make sure that all Assists have the same format in the raid.  People get confused with 3 conletely different appearing assist messages, try to make it uniform and it'll go better.<br>
<br>
Another word, if you are &quot;main assist&quot; whatever you do....never ever ever change targets.    Your Secondary and Third assists can generally deal with any threat while you finish what you've committed to.   If you are all over the place, confusion and disorganization occurs and people die FAST.  Finally, if multiple monsters have been mesmerized, and by the time you're done killing one, another beomes unmezzed, target the unmezzed one, don't make your enchanter go and mez it again while you break another mez.<br>
<br>
Also, keep in communication with your pullers.  They will generally tell you when to &quot;tag&quot;, when it's more or less &quot;safe&quot;.<br>
<br>
<br>
Raid Type 2:  Zone Raids with Unmezzable targets<br>
<br>
There are some raids where some different tactics are required.   The classic example of this is the Kael Arena.   Giants there cannot be mezzed, and everything must have a tank to keep it busy.  Generally speaking, aggro begins to become an issue here.  These guys hit hard, and the person best suited for taking those blows should be the Main Assist, Second assist the same, and so on.  THis is where positioning of forces begins to come into play as well.   <br>
<br>
The best positioning is this:   Main Tank in front of the monster, the rest behind him, or flanking him.  Each person has a responsibility to help the Main Tank maintain aggro so that he's the only one being beaten upon.  This is the beginning of what you'll need to be aware of throughout your whole EQ career.  When in front of a monster, he can riposte, and these guys, as I said earlier hit very hard.  You really don't want your healing to be spread out across the raid if it can be avoided by simple positioning, so if you're not tanking, you should be behind or flanking.<br>
<br>
Main Assist/tank's job is a little easier here, all he really needs to do is identify the greatest threat and target and attack.  A little &quot;pre-taunt&quot; is a good idea here, let the main tank dance alone with the monster for a while so that when the rest join, the monster's attention is solidly focused on the Main Tank.   Generally, healer monsters are the greatest threat, because they'll stop what their doing to heal other monsters who are hurt in the area, and this can drag out for some time.  Get rid of the healers, and you will shorten the fights, and increase the rate of killing.  Other examples where these tactics are used is in the Temple of Veeshan West and Halls of Testing.<br>
<br>
Raid type 3:  Single Large target monsters<br>
<br>
There comes a time when you must refine your tactics even further... this is in reference to a single target high damage output monster, such as Velketor the Sorcerer or Derakor the Vindicator.  There are what is called &quot;gateway mobs&quot; as once you begin to know how to defeat these monsters, you've opened up the rest of Everquest to your raiding party/guild, etc.<br>
<br>
Guys like this have very heavy melee capabilities, and if they bounce around to different people will destroy a raid before you can blink an eye.  What you need here is to TRULY focus the monster's attacks on one person, the Main Tank.  This tank will geneally be healed with what's called a &quot;Complete Heal Rotation&quot; where clerics will cast &quot;Complete Heal&quot; in timed intervals to ensure that the person being beaten upon remains alive.  The rest must try as hard as they can not to pull the attention of the monster away from the &quot;main tank&quot;.  This can be devastating.    Again, Main tank in front, takes the initial onslaught of attacks.   In some circles, it's deemed proper for the Main Tank to call the beginning of the Complete heal rotation.  If you do this, I'd recommend a hotkey which says &quot;BEGIN HEALING NOW&quot; or something to that effect.<br>
<br>
If it's your first few times doing this monster, then /disc defensive before engaging is a good idea.   After your clerics are used to it, it doesn't matter really, but for the first few times, it's probably quite crucial.<br>
<br>
In instances like this, you'll want to have an established &quot;tank order&quot; so that if/when the first tank dies, everyone backs off and allows the new one to generate aggro and gain the monster's attention, and to shift the rotation to him.  Tank switches are ugly and can prove to be the downfall of some raids.  It's usually best not to have them, but it's not a bad idea to know how to do it, because I guarantee when you face the Avatar of War for the first time, you'll be seeing tank switching and how fast 50 people can melt from full health to nothing.<br>
<br>
Generally most encounters are similar to this some with different features, things that make them unique, but they tend to follow this pattern through the rest of Velious/Luclin.<br>
<br>
It's only when you get to Deep Luclin that there's more insane encounters, and by the time you're able to do those, you should be able to figure out how to handle them.<br>
<br>
That's all I can think of for the moment, but I'm sure that I'll come up with more later.<br>
