<br>
-To me a warrior is a person who needs to be very aware of everything going on, at all times. If assigned to main tank, communication is vital. Be in communication with your leader, pull team, heal channel, etc. Be sure to know whats going on when and how, down to a point. Be aware of where the monsters are relative to you and other monsters. Be aware of who and where other players are attacking from or positioned. If you see something incorrect, communicate it fast and get it fixed. Be aware of your buffs at all times, your discipline timers and such. Basically, just watch your ass and everyone elses ass at all times.<br>
<br>
-When not the main tank, but on the lineup, its important to still be listening in the channels, know whats going on. Always, be in the know.<br>
<br>
-Know your foe and the geography. If its the first time to be at a zone do some online research. Get to the various class boards and databases and look around. As the old saying goes, knowledge is power. Know the abilities and weaknesses of the mobs. Know damage intervals and bonuses. Know what you can do to be the most efficient at killing and tanking a foe.<br>
<br>
-Have a versatile lineup of equipment. Warriors by design are heavily dependant on other classes. That, well, sucks. Have items to facilitate raids. Have a selection of instant click items for battling dispellers. A cobalt bracer is a nice item for helping to shrink a raid faster. A fungal tunic is great when your not tanking for helping mitigate area effect damage. Access to invisibility items, see invis, levitate, spirit of the wolf, items all help in mobilizing to a raid and lowering your dependancy on others. Having a few items that you can use to buff yourself never hurts as well for the odd situation. Be a boyscout.<br>
<br>
-Have a versatile lineup of weaponry. A warrior has no spells, no abilities, weapons are your tools, and a carpenter doesnt go to work with just a hammer. Situational weaponry. Have your taunting weapons for main tanking and have a good dps setup for non tanking. A good mix of procs for different situations. Know when and how to use your tools to the best of ability.<br>
<br>
-Know game mechanics. A warrior is left without abilities or spells. To reiterate, knowledge is power. Always be on top of your game.<br>
<br>
-When simply support tanking use your dps setup. Do not crowd the main tank, your not supposed to be trying ti hold the attention of the mob in this situation. Fight behind or flank mobs to avoid its defensive capabilites and eating silly riposte damage. Always be ready to jump at a moments notice. For either having to step to the plate as main tank or add tanking.<br>
<br>
-Don't blow disciplines like a fool. You cannot afford wasting a timer. Always good to have evasive or defensive ready to go if the situation arises. If you <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> know</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> you will not be tanking, instructed to, use the best offensive discipline for the situation. On longer fights aggressive is very attractive due to its 3minute duration and is a decent increase in your dps. On some of the shorter fights, oh say Kunark level stuff, I fellstrike will do just fine.<br>
<br>
-Before the raid have your stuff together. If you need arrows summoned or such, get it done before any combat happens.<br>
<br>
-Back to the knowing your foe business, on some of the crawl style raids, know what is and is not mezzable so you don't tank mez something the robed chanter beside you is trying to mez. They get a bit pissy.<br>
<br>
-Before raids, get there fast. So if your unfamiliar with the area, print some maps off.<br>
<br>
-Always play well. Yah, sounds retarded but I personally get a bit upset by people who go lazy on raids and stop watching what their doing and make small screwups. A rogue gets lazy he may get pounded on a sec, you get lazy and some fanged behemoth wipes half your force. Don't F up.<br>
<br>
-Stand still. Listen to orders. Shut up. Goes for anyone. Paying attention and coordinating does wonders. Panicking, looking around, blabbing in chat just gets people dead.<br>
<br>
-Have some knowledge of what other classes should be doing. Knowing how everything melds together helps alot.<br>
<br>
-Know your buffs. And be sure to aquire them with what ever method your raid leader has instructed. <br>
<br>
-When main tanking, if you see people doing something incorrect, obstructing you, pushing the mob the wrong way, or pulling aggro, it is your right to bitch. Get their ass in place.<br>
<br>
-On many higher end encounters, the mobs are rooted. Make sure your raid leader gives you time to pre-establish some aggro the target. Plugging arrows into the mobs side works nicely. Also, some items with right click effects can work nice to. One example is a bioluminescent orb. Firing arrows is funner tho! And if your archery isn't capped, couple skill ups are fun to see scroll by.<br>
<br>
-Always be sure to let it be known if you need to go afk. Autofollow a group member. Pick one that won't make you wander off and get stuck behind a door and try to kill you. Assholes. Don't just tell one person. Make sure that everyone knows! Talk with your raid leader and let him know how long ya going to be away and such. It is his job to then appoint a new main tank or assist or what have ya.<br>
<br>
-Choose a wise alternate advancement path. For general skills, runspeed3 is essential imo. Whatever other 3 you wish is fine then. Archtype should max Natural Durability asap. Follow that with class skill area effect taunt. After that you will want physical enchancement and combat agility3. Those I consider the essentials. Tailor everything afterwards to your style of play and how you are employed on raids.<br>
<br>
-Be smart with add tanking. Communicate which mob you intend to tank mez. Don't fight with another warrior for aggro on a mob he already called. Thats silly. Also, if not the main tank or addtank, and merely support taning, I do not suggest breaking away from your MA's target to 'help' kill a mob another person has tank mezzed, unless specifically instructed. Splitting dps is retarded in most situations. When tank mezzing control where your mob is. During this time you have complete control of the mob. Put him where your leader wants him dead. I always will pull a mob away from the main target just to lessen confusion. <br>
<br>
-If you are mez tanking, once the MA clears his mob, it is best if you tank your mob to death. The Main tank should call which target he wants dead next, but in most cases it is just silly if he tries to outaggro you. Just causes healers confusion or wasted mana. You locked that add onto you, you finish it.<br>
<br>
-When not tanking, if not on a tank lineup, don't get aggro. Yah, shove those proccing taunt weapons in a bag and use that weapon for this situation we discussed earlier. Also, since warriors lack any kind of aggro evasive skills, you have the ability to turn off attack! So do that once in a while. Watch your damage spam and if your on a 'kick ass streak' take a second or three break from attacks. Also, make like the other melee and fight at max melee range and do not draw unneeded attention. So, do not hit your taunt button or disarm or call his mother names.<br>
<br>
-When not tanking, but lets say second in line, learn to manipulate your aggro. You want to be pretty close to the top of the mobs effective hate list. In this scenario, using a weapon with a taunt proc is alright to keep yourself up there. It takes some experience really. I personally sort of visualize the order of aggro and whats going on, what each action I perform does and such. Yah..<br>
<br>
Course, if your raiding some higher end content you will proba<br>
bly have area effect taunt, which makes this all much simpler. Area effect taunt, if it works, will always place you to the top of the hate list. While some situations, namely low life aggro, can override this, you are still top of the list, just you look tasty all bleeding and @#%$. Anyway, AE taunt lets you grab aggro instantly, so working hard to stay right below the main tank isn't really a big issue.<br>
<br>
-Use AE taunt effectively. It will always give you aggro, however, it gives but a slight edge as 'most hated person.' This means that another person, right below the warrior aggro wise, could take aggro if hes not careful. It is usually wise to let it be known when you are going to fire AE taunt, so people can prepare for the change of the mobs target, healing reasons, and the above stated aggro reason. This is a warriors best skill, learn how to use it well. Tank switches, aquiring an add target easily, pulling an incorrectly placed mob out of a wall, saving some asses, or what have you. 15 min refresh so use wisely.<br>
<br>
-Be properly nourished. Eat a good breakfast on a day you know your raiding an uber mob. Plenty of sleep the night before as well!<br>
<br>
-In the event of a large overpull where a campout is instructed, unless told otherwise, you don't. Get out there and fight to the death with some dignity! Part of a raiding warriors life, accept that your going to die, and die alot. You are the piece of meat that the wolves tear into shreads while the little girls run away.<br>
<br>
-Make note of things you see that are incorrect or could be done better. Communicate this to your leader afterwards. It is usually best not to swamp the leader in the middle of the raid. Hes busy with things. If you know something that is imperative to success, do let him know though. Just dont bitch and moan to him or in raid chat while its occuring. Create your own chat channel for bitching.<br>
<br>
-(Tidbits for MT)<br>
When main tanking, give instructions for what you need done. Have people wait to attack untill you are ready. Establish some aggro and when your comfortable call em in. Some people alot different lengths of time. The people I had played with were always pretty quick on the tirgger finger so I'd do 10sec or so and decrease depending on how many procs I would get during that time. /shrug<br>
<br>
 Make sure people aren't crowding you. If the mob is being pushed the wrong way do your part to adjust and also instruct people on what to do. <br>
<br>
Evaluate which discipline works best for the encounter. On some of the higher end mobs a riposte can be to damaging to risk with dual weildling. In times where your discipline is down many prefer switching to a nice two hander for cutting potential riposte damage. <br>
<br>
Keep a close proximity. Do what you can to piss it off as much as possible. The disarm skill refreshes fast and does add a minimal amount of aggro, every little bit can help for some people I guess. Also nice as a 'rangefinder' for some of the big mobs to tell if your close enough or whatnot.<br>
 <br>
I tend to use 'walk' instead of having 'run' toggled on once I engage a mob. Gives a little more control of movement and staying close while doing so. <br>
<br>
Use Area taunt if a situation arises to grab aggro back fast.If you lose aggro command people to stop attacking- they should use aggro evasive skills and not swing. Once you regain aggro and are comfortable call them back in. <br>
<br>
Watch heal spam. You know how much damage your taking, alert healers if they are at a to fast or to slow pace. Announce when discipline has run out so peopel can adjust. <br>
<br>
If your cornering and getting a good number of &quot;you cannot see target&quot; message, looking up and backwalking seems to help some people. <br>
<br>
If a mob gets pushed somewhere you don't want, you can call off attacks and try to move him, or even move him without calling off attack if you feel comfortable. If aggro is solid back up fast to the area you want. You will be summoned, just back up fast again and the mob will walk right over. Kinda fun little rubber band action. <br>
<br>
Communicate your intentions at all times. Let the raid know if your turning the mob, moving it, whatever. <br>
<br>
Be aware of special attacks and call for special needs as required. Diseases curses or whatever. Stop attacking when a mob enrages. <br>
<br>
Get shrunk or grown as a raid demands. From a halfling perspective, I find it easier to tank when grown up. Increases mobility and just find it more confortable. Some mobs you will need to be shrunk to get in a corner or whatever, just know the encounter. Levitate works wonders for short warriors in the zones its allowed. <br>
<br>
Pan your views as needed. The overhead view is very very helpful. Set camera angles prior to engagement so you can get a quick glance at surroundings mid fight. <br>
<br>
When mobs are being pulled to you, stand forward of the rest of the raid a bit to help establish a quick response to the enemy.<br>
<br>
Backing up and sitting can work as a quick way of moving a mob to you. Learning the timing so as to not get smacked for full damage is a plus.<br>
<br>
Have buffs organized. I aways keep at least one instant click buff in the top slots incase of dispellers. Habit now and its like this even when I know there will not be. Make sure to have the buffs required to get the job done. Fancy extra stuff you can toss away to make slots for heal over times, bard songs, more instant clickies if the situation needs, aggro manipulating spells, whatever. Always leave room. 15 buff limit. <br>
<br>
Be sure you are wearing the right gear before you tank. If switching around alot from main tank to secondary or whatever, have the right tools geared up. Assume your going to get your asskicked and go for the hitpoints. So switch off that fungi tunic and throw on your 100-125hp breastplate of tanking. Dont make a silly mistake and have the incorrect weapons out either.<br>
<br>
Uber mobs, that is your 65+ mobs, are immune to taunt. Quit mashing it!<br>
<br>
On a less than uber mob, don't mash taunt either. It does nothing. Save it for an instance where you lose aggro and hope it works. <br>
<br>
-Instant clickies. Great to have. A main tank should have at least a few at his disposal. These allow a warrior to throw up 1-4 junk buffs to suck up mob dispells. Also, its always nice to be able to arrange your top few buffs on the fly. Say a green drake is incoming and you hate that slow they always land on you. Yah, dont we all. So, drop your top few instant clickies and allow it to settle up there. Once hes disposed, simply have it dispelled, and toss back up your junkies. <br>
<br>
A quick list of a few would be your 8-10th coldain rings, shrunken goblin skill earring, journeyman's boots, amulet of necropotence. These all do not require targeting yourself to cast. If your feeling really dextrous with hotkeys and the tab button, there are a few more instant clicks that require yourself being targetted. This ofcourse means you may lose an attack round or two but if your quick.. <br>
<br>
-Hotkeys. Make a few banks and use them. Clumsily opening menus or clicking stuff wastes time. Typing out commands takes a second or two and draws your attention. So, prepare with hotkeys. Do pretty much everything with keyboard shortcuts.<br>
<br>
-Except movement. Mouselook movement is more precise and controllable than keyboard movement. I prefer the tight control granted with this. When tanking, holding right mouse and left clicking, taps, can make some minor adjustments. Also strafing helps to position yourelf the way you want. Walk mode instead of run mode for greater precision.<br>
<br>
In summary I guess it comes down to:<br>
1)Knowledge is power.<br>
2)Be prepared.<br>
3)Pay attention to everything. Be alert.<br>
4)Shush and listen to orders.<br>
5)Communication is everything.<br>
6)Always be organized in detail. Chaos is a wipe.<br>
<br>
All I have for now. I apologize for some of the randomness of it, lack of organization. Just plopped down thoughts while watching television. <br>
